/*
 * OCR A-Level Economics (H460) — Practice Question Bank
 * 8 granular topics: 1.1-1.4 (Microeconomics), 2.1-2.4 (Macroeconomics)
 * 40 questions per topic (320 total), mix of 1-6 marks.
 * Uses markScheme with bullet points and (1) per marking point.
 * diagram: true on questions requiring students to draw/sketch/use a diagram.
 */
const ECONOMICS_OCR_PRACTICE = {
  '1.1': {
    name: 'Economic Problem & Market Systems',
    questions: [
      { q: 'State what is meant by the economic problem.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) Resources/factors of production are scarce/limited relative to unlimited wants.' },
      { q: 'Identify two factors of production other than land.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Labour — human effort used in production. (1) Capital — man-made resources used to produce goods/services. (Accept enterprise.)' },
      { q: 'Define opportunity cost.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The next best alternative (1) forgone/given up when a choice is made.' },
      { q: 'Draw a production possibility frontier and show the effect of economic growth.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Correctly drawn PPF with axes labelled (two goods). (1) Outward shift of the PPF. (1) Annotation showing increased maximum output of both goods is now possible.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a point inside the PPF represents an inefficient allocation of resources.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) A point inside the PPF means not all resources are being fully utilised. (1) It would be possible to produce more of one or both goods without sacrificing the other.' },
      { q: 'State two determinants of demand other than price.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Income of consumers. (1) Prices of substitutes or complements. (Accept: tastes/preferences, population, advertising, expectations.)' },
      { q: 'Using a demand and supply diagram, show the effect of a rise in raw material costs on the market for bread.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Correctly drawn initial equilibrium (D and S curves with P and Q labelled). (1) Supply curve shifts to the left (S to S1). (1) New higher equilibrium price shown. (1) New lower equilibrium quantity shown.' },
      { q: 'Calculate the PED if a 10% rise in price causes a 25% fall in quantity demanded.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) PED = % change in Qd / % change in P = -25/10. (1) PED = -2.5 (accept 2.5 in absolute terms).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the demand for salt is likely to be price inelastic.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Salt has few close substitutes. (1) It represents a small proportion of household income. (1) It is a necessity/habitual purchase, so consumers are less responsive to price changes.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between a movement along and a shift of the supply curve.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) A movement along the supply curve is caused by a change in the price of the good itself. (1) A shift of the supply curve is caused by a change in a non-price factor (e.g., costs, technology, government policy). (1) A shift means more or less is supplied at every price level.' },
      { q: 'Define consumer surplus.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The difference between what consumers are willing to pay (1) and what they actually pay / the market price.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show consumer surplus and producer surplus at market equilibrium.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Correct supply and demand diagram with equilibrium P and Q. (1) Consumer surplus correctly identified as the area below the demand curve and above the price. (1) Producer surplus correctly identified as the area above the supply curve and below the price.' },
      { q: 'A good has a YED of -0.8. State whether it is a normal or inferior good and explain why.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) It is an inferior good. (1) Because YED is negative, meaning demand falls when income rises.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by joint supply and give an example.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Joint supply occurs when the production of one good leads to the production of another. (1) Example: beef and leather — producing beef also produces leather as a by-product.' },
      { q: 'Explain how the price mechanism allocates resources through the signalling function.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Rising prices signal to producers that a good is in greater demand. (1) This incentivises firms to allocate more resources to its production. (1) Falling prices signal reduced demand, causing resources to be reallocated away.' },
      { q: 'Draw a diagram showing the effect of an indirect tax on a market and identify the tax revenue.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Correct initial equilibrium. (1) Supply curve shifts up/left by the amount of the tax. (1) New higher equilibrium price and lower equilibrium quantity. (1) Tax revenue correctly shown as the shaded rectangle between old and new supply curves up to new equilibrium quantity.' },
      { q: 'State what XED measures.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) Cross elasticity of demand measures the responsiveness of demand for one good to a change in the price of another good.' },
      { q: 'The XED between goods A and B is +2.3. Explain the relationship between these goods.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The goods are substitutes (positive XED). (1) A 1% rise in the price of good B leads to a 2.3% increase in demand for good A — they are strong substitutes.' },
      { q: 'Explain why PES tends to be higher in the long run than in the short run.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) In the long run, all factors of production are variable. (1) Firms can build new factories, hire workers, and source materials. (1) In the short run, capacity constraints and fixed factors limit the ability to respond to price changes.' },
      { q: 'State the equilibrium condition in a market.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) Equilibrium occurs where quantity demanded equals quantity supplied (Qd = Qs) / where the demand and supply curves intersect.' },
      { q: 'Define producer surplus.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The difference between the price a producer receives (1) and the minimum price they would be willing to accept / their cost of production.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the effect of a maximum price (price ceiling) set below the market equilibrium.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Correct demand and supply diagram with initial equilibrium. (1) Maximum price correctly drawn below equilibrium price. (1) Excess demand / shortage shown (Qd > Qs at the maximum price). (1) The quantity actually traded is the lower quantity supplied.' },
      { q: 'Calculate the YED given that a 5% increase in income leads to a 15% increase in demand for restaurant meals.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) YED = % change in Qd / % change in income = 15/5. (1) YED = +3.0 (positive, so it is a normal good / luxury).' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between a substitute and a complement in demand.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) A substitute is a good that can be used in place of another — a rise in the price of one increases demand for the other. (1) A complement is a good used together with another — a rise in the price of one reduces demand for the other.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the supply of housing is likely to be price inelastic in the short run.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Land is fixed in supply / limited planning permissions. (1) Building new homes takes a long time (construction lags). (1) Factors of production in construction cannot be easily or quickly increased.' },
      { q: 'Draw a diagram showing a perfectly elastic demand curve and state the PED value.', marks: 2, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Horizontal demand curve correctly drawn at a given price. (1) PED = infinity (perfectly elastic).' },
      { q: 'A firm raises its price by 20% and total revenue falls. Explain whether demand is elastic or inelastic.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Demand is price elastic (PED > 1). (1) Because the percentage fall in quantity demanded is greater than the 20% price rise, so total revenue (P x Q) falls.' },
      { q: 'Using a supply and demand diagram, show the effect of a subsidy on the market for electric vehicles.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Correct initial equilibrium with demand and supply. (1) Supply curve shifts to the right/down by the amount of the subsidy. (1) New lower equilibrium price for consumers. (1) New higher equilibrium quantity.' },
      { q: 'State the three functions of the price mechanism.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Signalling — prices signal to producers and consumers where resources are needed. (1) Incentive — price changes create incentives for producers to supply more/less. (1) Rationing — prices ration scarce goods among those willing and able to pay.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the demand curve for a Veblen good might be upward sloping.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) A Veblen good is a luxury good whose appeal increases with price (conspicuous consumption). (1) Consumers derive utility from the status of owning an expensive item. (1) A higher price signals exclusivity and desirability, increasing quantity demanded.' },
      { q: 'State the formula for PES.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) PES = percentage change in quantity supplied / percentage change in price.' },
      { q: 'Explain why agricultural goods tend to have low PES.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Agricultural production has long time lags (crops take time to grow / livestock to rear). (1) Land suitable for farming is limited and difficult to expand quickly. (1) Perishability means output cannot be easily stored to respond to price changes.' },
      { q: 'A market is in equilibrium. Explain the adjustment process if demand suddenly increases.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) An increase in demand creates excess demand at the original price. (1) Consumers bid up the price / compete for the limited supply. (1) Higher prices incentivise producers to increase output (movement along supply). (1) The market reaches a new equilibrium at a higher price and higher quantity.' },
      { q: 'Define derived demand and give an example.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Derived demand is demand for a good/factor that arises from the demand for another good or service. (1) Example: demand for steel is derived from demand for cars / demand for labour is derived from demand for the product the workers produce.' },
      { q: 'Explain why an increase in the minimum wage could lead to either an increase or decrease in employment, depending on the market structure.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) In a competitive labour market, a minimum wage above equilibrium causes excess supply of labour / unemployment. (1) Firms demand fewer workers at the higher wage. (1) However, in a monopsony labour market, a minimum wage can increase both wages and employment. (1) Because the monopsonist was previously restricting employment below the competitive level to keep wages down.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the effect of a minimum price (price floor) set above equilibrium in the EU agricultural market.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Correct supply and demand diagram with equilibrium. (1) Minimum price drawn above equilibrium. (1) Excess supply / surplus shown (Qs > Qd at the minimum price). (1) Government must buy up the surplus or restrict supply to maintain the floor.' },
      { q: 'Calculate PES if a 15% rise in the price of strawberries leads to a 5% increase in quantity supplied.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) PES = % change in Qs / % change in P = 5/15. (1) PES = 0.33 (price inelastic supply).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the free market may not provide goods with positive externalities in sufficient quantities.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) In a free market, consumers consider only their private benefit (MPB), not the external benefit to third parties. (1) Therefore the market equilibrium quantity (where MPB = MPC) is below the socially optimal quantity (where MSB = MSC). (1) The good is underconsumed / underproduced because the full social benefit is not captured in the price.' },
      { q: 'Draw a diagram showing the effect of a fall in the exchange rate on the domestic market for imported goods.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Correct supply and demand diagram for imported goods. (1) Supply shifts left / price of imports rises (foreign goods cost more in domestic currency). (1) New equilibrium shows higher price and lower quantity of imported goods.' },
      { q: 'Explain how asymmetric information can lead to market failure in the second-hand car market.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Sellers have more information about the quality of their car than buyers (information asymmetry). (1) Buyers cannot distinguish good cars from bad, so they offer a low average price. (1) Owners of good cars withdraw from the market (adverse selection), leaving only lower-quality cars / the market for good cars collapses.' }
    ]
  },
  '1.2': {
    name: 'Market Failure & Government Intervention',
    questions: [
      { q: 'Define market failure.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) When the free market fails to allocate resources efficiently / does not achieve allocative efficiency / leads to a misallocation of resources.' },
      { q: 'State two types of market failure.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Externalities (positive or negative). (1) Public goods / information failure / monopoly power. (Any two valid types.)' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show how a negative externality in production leads to overproduction.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Correctly drawn diagram with MPC (supply) and MPB (demand) curves. (1) MSC curve drawn above MPC showing external costs. (1) Free market equilibrium at MPC = MPB shown. (1) Socially optimal output at MSC = MSB shown to the left, demonstrating overproduction.' },
      { q: 'Explain why public goods are not provided by the free market.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Public goods are non-excludable — non-payers cannot be prevented from consuming. (1) This creates the free rider problem — consumers have no incentive to pay. (1) Without a price mechanism, firms cannot generate revenue, so have no incentive to provide the good.' },
      { q: 'Distinguish between a merit good and a public good.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) A merit good is rival and excludable but underconsumed due to positive externalities and information failure. (1) A public good is non-rival and non-excludable. (1) Merit goods can be provided by the market (but in insufficient quantities), while public goods cannot be provided by the market due to the free rider problem.' },
      { q: 'State one example of information failure in the market for healthcare.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) Patients may not have the medical knowledge to judge the quality or necessity of treatment / asymmetric information between doctor and patient.' },
      { q: 'Explain how a subsidy can correct the underconsumption of a merit good.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) A merit good is underprovided because MSB > MPB. (1) A subsidy reduces the price, increasing quantity demanded towards the socially optimal level. (1) The subsidy should equal the marginal external benefit to internalise the positive externality.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show how a Pigouvian tax corrects a negative externality.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Diagram showing MSC above MPC with demand (MPB = MSB). (1) Tax equal to the marginal external cost applied to producers. (1) Supply shifts up so that the new supply curve aligns with MSC. (1) New equilibrium output equals the socially optimal output.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by the Coase theorem.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) If property rights are clearly defined and transaction costs are low, (1) private bargaining between parties can resolve externalities without government intervention / reach the socially optimal outcome.' },
      { q: 'State two causes of government failure.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Imperfect information leading to incorrect policy decisions. (1) Unintended consequences / distortion of market incentives. (Accept: regulatory capture, administrative costs, political short-termism.)' },
      { q: 'Explain why a ban on smoking in all public places might be considered a form of government intervention that risks government failure.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) A total ban removes consumer choice / paternalistic. (1) It may lead to unintended consequences such as loss of business for pubs and clubs. (1) Enforcement is costly and may be difficult / black market activity in enclosed spaces.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between private costs and external costs.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Private costs are costs borne by the economic agent making the decision (producer or consumer). (1) External costs are costs imposed on third parties not directly involved in the transaction.' },
      { q: 'Define moral hazard and give one example.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Moral hazard occurs when one party takes greater risks because they are protected from the consequences (e.g., by insurance). (1) Example: a person with car insurance may drive less carefully because they know damage will be covered.' },
      { q: 'Explain how tradeable pollution permits work to reduce carbon emissions.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) A government sets a total cap on carbon emissions. (1) Permits are allocated or auctioned to firms allowing them to emit a certain amount. (1) Firms that can reduce emissions cheaply can sell surplus permits to firms with higher abatement costs. (1) This creates a financial incentive for all firms to reduce emissions over time while achieving the cap cost-effectively.' },
      { q: 'State what is meant by a quasi-public good.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) A good that has some but not all characteristics of a public good. (1) It may be partially non-rival or partially non-excludable but not fully both, e.g., roads which can become congested (rival) or tolled (excludable).' },
      { q: 'Explain one advantage of using nudges rather than taxation to reduce unhealthy eating.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Nudges preserve freedom of choice / are not paternalistic. (1) They can be effective at changing behaviour without imposing a financial burden on consumers, particularly low-income households.' },
      { q: 'State the formula for social cost.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) Social cost = private cost + external cost.' },
      { q: 'Explain why common pool resources tend to be overexploited.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Common pool resources are rivalrous — one person\'s use reduces availability. (1) They are non-excludable — access cannot easily be restricted. (1) Without property rights or regulation, individuals have an incentive to overuse the resource (tragedy of the commons).' },
      { q: 'Explain one limitation of using information provision to correct market failure in the market for tobacco.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Consumers may be aware of the risks but still consume due to addiction / bounded rationality. (1) Information alone may not be sufficient to change behaviour if other factors (social norms, habit, addiction) are strong.' },
      { q: 'Distinguish between regulation and a market-based approach to correcting market failure.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Regulation uses laws/rules to directly control behaviour (e.g., banning emissions above a level). (1) Market-based approaches use price incentives (taxes, permits, subsidies) to change behaviour while preserving choice.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show how a positive externality in consumption leads to underconsumption.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Correctly drawn diagram with MPC (supply) and MPB (demand) curves. (1) MSB curve drawn above/to the right of MPB showing external benefits. (1) Free market equilibrium at MPC = MPB shown. (1) Socially optimal output at MSC = MSB shown to the right, demonstrating underconsumption.' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of adverse selection and give one example.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Adverse selection occurs when information asymmetry leads to one party making decisions that disadvantage the other. (1) Before a transaction, the party with more information can exploit this advantage. (1) Example: in health insurance, those most likely to be ill are most likely to buy insurance, driving up premiums for all.' },
      { q: 'State the formula for social benefit.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) Social benefit = private benefit + external benefit.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a demerit good is overconsumed in a free market.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Consumers underestimate the private costs (information failure / bounded rationality). (1) There are negative externalities to third parties (MSC > MPC). (1) The free market output exceeds the socially optimal output because the full social costs are not reflected in the price.' },
      { q: 'Evaluate the use of road pricing (congestion charges) to reduce traffic congestion in cities.', marks: 6, markScheme: '(1) Road pricing internalises the external cost of congestion by making drivers pay for the negative externality. (1) It reduces demand for road space during peak times, lowering congestion and journey times. (1) Revenue generated can fund public transport improvements. (1) However, it may be regressive — lower-income drivers are priced off the road while wealthier drivers are unaffected. (1) Enforcement and technology costs can be high. (1) Drivers may divert to uncharged routes, shifting congestion rather than eliminating it.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by regulatory capture.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Regulatory capture occurs when a regulator acts in the interests of the industry it is supposed to regulate rather than in the public interest. (1) This can happen because firms lobby regulators, offer future employment, or have superior technical knowledge.' },
      { q: 'Draw a diagram showing the welfare loss from a negative externality in production.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Correct diagram with MSC above MPC and demand (MPB = MSB). (1) Free market output (Qm) and socially optimal output (Qs) clearly identified. (1) Welfare/deadweight loss triangle correctly shaded between MSC and MSB from Qs to Qm.' },
      { q: 'Explain one reason why government provision of a merit good might lead to government failure.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The government may lack information about the optimal quantity to provide / cannot easily determine consumer preferences. (1) State provision may be inefficient due to lack of profit motive / X-inefficiency / bureaucratic waste.' },
      { q: 'State two characteristics of a public good.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Non-rival — one person\'s consumption does not reduce the amount available for others. (1) Non-excludable — it is not possible to prevent non-payers from consuming the good.' },
      { q: 'Explain how bounded rationality contributes to the overconsumption of demerit goods.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Bounded rationality means consumers do not always make fully rational decisions due to cognitive limitations. (1) They may underweight future costs (present bias / hyperbolic discounting) when consuming goods like alcohol or tobacco. (1) Even with full information available, consumers may not process it rationally, leading to choices that reduce their long-term welfare.' },
      { q: 'Explain one reason why minimum unit pricing for alcohol might be more effective than a tax on alcohol.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) A minimum unit price targets the cheapest, strongest drinks most associated with harmful consumption. (1) Unlike a tax, it cannot be absorbed by retailers or offset by promotions — it guarantees a floor price per unit of alcohol.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show how a quota corrects overproduction caused by a negative externality.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Correct externality diagram showing MSC above MPC with free market overproduction. (1) Quota set at the socially optimal quantity (where MSC = MSB). (1) Supply becomes vertical at the quota quantity. (1) Output reduced from free market level to socially optimal level.' },
      { q: 'Explain why extending property rights might not always solve the problem of negative externalities.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Transaction costs may be too high for affected parties to bargain effectively (violating the Coase theorem assumption). (1) The number of affected parties may be very large (e.g., air pollution affects millions), making negotiation impractical. (1) Power imbalances may mean polluters can impose costs on less powerful stakeholders.' },
      { q: 'State one difference between a specific tax and an ad valorem tax.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) A specific tax is a fixed amount per unit (e.g., 50p per litre), while an ad valorem tax is a percentage of the price (e.g., 20% VAT).' },
      { q: 'Explain how asymmetric information can lead to market failure in the insurance market.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Buyers of insurance know more about their own risk level than insurers (hidden information). (1) High-risk individuals are more likely to buy insurance, pushing up premiums. (1) This drives lower-risk people out of the market (adverse selection), potentially causing the market to collapse / only insure the highest risks.' },
      { q: 'Evaluate the effectiveness of information provision as a policy to reduce obesity.', marks: 6, markScheme: '(1) Calorie labelling and health campaigns increase consumer awareness of risks. (1) Information is non-distortionary — it does not restrict choice or impose costs on firms. (1) However, obesity is influenced by habitual behaviour, addiction to sugar/fat, and bounded rationality. (1) Information may only influence those already health-conscious, not those most at risk. (1) The food industry may respond with confusing labelling or marketing that undermines the information. (1) Evidence suggests information alone has limited impact — more effective when combined with other interventions.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between a negative externality in consumption and a negative externality in production.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) A negative externality in consumption occurs when the act of consuming imposes costs on third parties (e.g., passive smoking from cigarettes). (1) A negative externality in production occurs when the act of producing imposes costs on third parties (e.g., factory pollution affecting nearby residents).' },
      { q: 'State two limitations of tradeable pollution permits.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Permits must be set at the right level — too generous and emissions are not reduced. (1) Monitoring and enforcement is costly and complex / firms may cheat without proper oversight. (Accept: permits may concentrate pollution in certain areas, or firms may pass costs to consumers.)' },
      { q: 'Explain how government failure can arise from political short-termism.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Politicians face election cycles of 4-5 years, incentivising policies with short-term visible benefits rather than long-term structural improvements. (1) This may lead to underinvestment in infrastructure, education, or climate change mitigation where benefits materialise beyond the electoral cycle.' },
      { q: 'Explain one way in which behavioural economics challenges the assumption of rational consumers in traditional market failure analysis.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Traditional economics assumes consumers are rational utility maximisers with consistent preferences. (1) Behavioural economics shows consumers are subject to biases (e.g., anchoring, framing, loss aversion, status quo bias). (1) This means market failure may be more widespread than traditional analysis suggests, as consumers systematically fail to maximise their own welfare even with perfect information.' }
    ]
  },
  '1.3': {
    name: 'Firm Objectives, Costs & Revenue',
    questions: [
      { q: 'State the formula for profit.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) Profit = Total Revenue - Total Cost (or TR - TC).' },
      { q: 'Define average cost.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) Total cost divided by the quantity of output produced (AC = TC/Q).' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between fixed costs and variable costs.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Fixed costs do not change with the level of output in the short run (e.g., rent, salaries). (1) Variable costs change directly with the level of output (e.g., raw materials, energy).' },
      { q: 'A firm has total costs of £500,000 and produces 10,000 units. Calculate the average cost.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) AC = £500,000 / 10,000 = £50 per unit.' },
      { q: 'Explain the law of diminishing marginal returns.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) In the short run, at least one factor is fixed. (1) As additional units of the variable factor are added, output initially rises at an increasing rate. (1) Beyond a certain point, each additional unit of the variable factor adds less to total output (diminishing marginal product).' },
      { q: 'Draw a diagram showing the relationship between marginal cost and average cost curves.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) U-shaped AC curve correctly drawn. (1) U-shaped MC curve correctly drawn. (1) MC intersects AC at its minimum point.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the MC curve cuts the AC curve at its lowest point.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) When MC < AC, producing an extra unit brings down the average — so AC is falling. (1) When MC > AC, producing an extra unit raises the average — so AC is rising. (1) Therefore MC must equal AC exactly at the minimum point of the AC curve.' },
      { q: 'Distinguish between normal profit and supernormal profit.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Normal profit is the minimum return needed to keep a firm in the industry (TR = TC including opportunity cost). (1) Supernormal profit is any profit above normal profit (TR > TC / AR > AC).' },
      { q: 'State the profit-maximising rule.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) A firm maximises profit where MR = MC (and MC is rising / cuts MR from below).' },
      { q: 'Explain why a firm would shut down if price falls below average variable cost.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) If P < AVC, the firm cannot cover its variable costs of production. (1) Every unit produced adds to losses beyond the fixed costs. (1) The firm minimises losses by shutting down and only paying fixed costs.' },
      { q: 'State two types of internal economies of scale.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Technical economies — use of larger/more efficient machinery and production lines. (1) Purchasing/bulk-buying economies — lower input costs from large orders. (Accept: financial, managerial, risk-bearing, marketing.)' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by diseconomies of scale.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) When long-run average costs rise as the firm increases output / grows beyond a certain size. (1) Often caused by communication difficulties, coordination problems, or loss of worker motivation in very large organisations.' },
      { q: 'Draw the long-run average cost curve showing economies and diseconomies of scale and label the minimum efficient scale.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Downward-sloping section showing economies of scale. (1) Flat/constant section or upward-sloping section showing diseconomies of scale. (1) LRAC curve correctly drawn as an envelope of SRAC curves. (1) MES correctly labelled at the output level where LRAC is first minimised.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by revenue maximisation and where it occurs.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Revenue maximisation is the output where total revenue is at its highest. (1) This occurs where MR = 0 / the midpoint of the demand curve for a linear demand curve.' },
      { q: 'State one reason why a firm might pursue an objective other than profit maximisation.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) Divorce of ownership and control — managers may pursue growth or revenue maximisation for personal benefit (salary, status). (Accept: satisficing, survival, social objectives, stakeholder interests.)' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by the principal-agent problem in the context of a public limited company.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The principal (shareholders) delegates decision-making to agents (managers). (1) Agents may pursue their own objectives (salary, perks, empire building) rather than profit maximisation. (1) Information asymmetry means shareholders cannot perfectly monitor managerial behaviour.' },
      { q: 'Explain one external economy of scale.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) External economies arise from the growth of the industry as a whole (not an individual firm). (1) Example: a concentration of tech firms in an area creates a pool of skilled labour that all firms benefit from / shared infrastructure / knowledge spillovers.' },
      { q: 'A firm sells 200 units at £10 each. Calculate total revenue.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) TR = P x Q = £10 x 200 = £2,000.' },
      { q: 'Explain why average revenue equals price for all firms.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Total revenue = P x Q. (1) Average revenue = TR / Q = (P x Q) / Q = P. Therefore AR always equals price.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between short-run and long-run time periods in economics.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) In the short run, at least one factor of production is fixed (cannot be changed). (1) In the long run, all factors of production are variable and firms can enter or exit the industry.' },
      { q: 'Define marginal cost.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) The additional cost of producing one more unit of output (MC = change in TC / change in Q).' },
      { q: 'A firm produces 100 units with total costs of £5,000 and 101 units with total costs of £5,060. Calculate the marginal cost of the 101st unit.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) MC = £5,060 - £5,000 = £60.' },
      { q: 'Explain the relationship between marginal product and marginal cost.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Marginal product is the additional output from one more unit of a variable factor. (1) When marginal product is rising (increasing returns), marginal cost is falling. (1) When marginal product is falling (diminishing returns), marginal cost is rising — they are inversely related.' },
      { q: 'Draw a diagram showing total cost, total variable cost, and total fixed cost curves.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) TFC drawn as a horizontal line (constant regardless of output). (1) TVC drawn as a curve starting from the origin, initially increasing at a decreasing rate then at an increasing rate. (1) TC drawn parallel to TVC but starting from the TFC level (TC = TFC + TVC).' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by satisficing behaviour.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Satisficing means achieving a satisfactory level of profit rather than the maximum possible. (1) Managers may pursue this to balance the interests of different stakeholders (shareholders, workers, customers) or to avoid the effort/risk of profit maximisation.' },
      { q: 'Explain how the separation of ownership and control can lead to allocative inefficiency.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Shareholders (owners) want profit maximisation which aligns with P = MC (allocative efficiency). (1) Managers may pursue growth or revenue maximisation, producing beyond the profit-maximising output. (1) Resources are not allocated to their highest-value use because output decisions do not reflect consumer valuations (P ≠ MC).' },
      { q: 'A firm has fixed costs of £200,000 and variable costs of £15 per unit. If it produces 10,000 units, calculate the average cost.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) TC = FC + VC = £200,000 + (£15 x 10,000) = £200,000 + £150,000 = £350,000. (1) AC = £350,000 / 10,000 = £35 per unit.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by a sunk cost and why it should not influence future decision-making.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) A sunk cost is a cost that has already been incurred and cannot be recovered (e.g., advertising expenditure, specialised equipment). (1) Rational firms should ignore sunk costs when making future decisions because they cannot be altered regardless of the decision taken (only future costs and revenues should matter).' },
      { q: 'Explain how financial economies of scale benefit large firms.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Large firms can borrow at lower interest rates because they are seen as lower risk / more creditworthy by banks. (1) They also have access to a wider range of finance sources (e.g., share issues, corporate bonds) that are unavailable to small firms.' },
      { q: 'Draw a diagram showing the short-run cost curves (MC, ATC, AVC, AFC) and explain their shapes.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) AFC drawn as a continuously falling curve (fixed costs spread over more units). (1) AVC drawn as a U-shape reflecting diminishing marginal returns. (1) ATC drawn as a U-shape above AVC (ATC = AVC + AFC). (1) MC drawn intersecting both AVC and ATC at their minimum points.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the LRAC curve is described as an envelope curve.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The LRAC is derived from the lowest points of all possible SRAC curves for different scales of production. (1) It envelopes/is tangent to all SRAC curves, showing the minimum cost of producing each output level when all factors can be varied.' },
      { q: 'A firm currently earns supernormal profit. Explain how this affects its long-run decision-making.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Supernormal profit signals that resources in this industry earn above their opportunity cost. (1) The firm will remain in the industry; new firms will be attracted to enter (if barriers are low), potentially eroding the supernormal profit over time.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by sales maximisation and how it differs from revenue maximisation.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Sales maximisation means producing the highest output possible while still making at least normal profit (AC = AR / breakeven constraint). (1) Revenue maximisation is producing where MR = 0 regardless of cost. (1) Sales maximisation typically produces a higher output than revenue maximisation because it pushes output further provided costs are covered.' },
      { q: 'State one reason why a firm might pursue a growth objective.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) Managers benefit from growth through higher salaries, prestige, and reduced risk of takeover. (Accept: economies of scale, market power, survival motivation.)' },
      { q: 'Explain how predatory pricing might be used as a strategy and why it involves short-run losses.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Predatory pricing involves setting price below AVC to drive competitors out of the market. (1) The firm incurs short-run losses because it cannot cover its costs at this price. (1) Once competitors exit, the firm can raise prices and exploit its monopoly position to recoup losses.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the difference between increasing, constant, and decreasing returns to scale on the LRAC.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Falling LRAC section correctly labelled as increasing returns to scale / economies of scale. (1) Flat/horizontal section correctly labelled as constant returns to scale. (1) Rising LRAC section correctly labelled as decreasing returns to scale / diseconomies of scale.' },
      { q: 'Explain one cause of diseconomies of scale.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) As firms grow very large, communication becomes more difficult across many departments and layers of management. (1) This leads to slower decision-making, loss of coordination, and reduced efficiency, raising average costs.' },
      { q: 'Calculate the marginal revenue if total revenue increases from £8,000 to £8,400 when output rises from 40 to 42 units.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Change in TR = £8,400 - £8,000 = £400. Change in Q = 42 - 40 = 2. (1) MR = £400 / 2 = £200 per unit.' },
      { q: 'Explain why MR is below AR for a firm facing a downward-sloping demand curve.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) To sell an additional unit, the firm must lower the price on all units (not just the marginal unit). (1) Total revenue from the extra unit is the new lower price, but revenue is lost on all previous units that could have been sold at the higher price. (1) Therefore MR (net gain from selling one more) is always less than AR (price) — the MR curve lies below the AR/demand curve.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by technical economies of scale and give one example.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Technical economies arise from the use of large-scale capital equipment that is more efficient per unit of output. (1) Example: a large container ship carries more goods per pound of fuel than a small vessel / the cube-square law means doubling dimensions increases volume eightfold but surface area only fourfold.' }
    ]
  },
  '1.4': {
    name: 'Market Structures',
    questions: [
      { q: 'State two characteristics of perfect competition.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Homogeneous/identical products. (1) Many buyers and sellers, each too small to influence price. (Accept: perfect information, no barriers to entry/exit, firms are price takers.)' },
      { q: 'Explain why a firm in perfect competition is a price taker.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Each firm produces a tiny proportion of total market output. (1) If it raises price above the market price, it loses all customers to identical competitors.' },
      { q: 'Draw a diagram showing short-run supernormal profit for a firm in perfect competition.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Horizontal demand/AR/MR curve at the market price. (1) U-shaped AC and MC curves. (1) Profit-maximising output where MC = MR. (1) Supernormal profit shown as the shaded area between AR and AC at profit-maximising output.' },
      { q: 'Explain why supernormal profits are competed away in perfect competition in the long run.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Supernormal profit attracts new firms into the industry (no barriers to entry). (1) Increased supply shifts the market supply curve right, reducing the market price. (1) Entry continues until P = AC and only normal profit is earned.' },
      { q: 'Define productive efficiency.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) Producing at the lowest possible average cost / at the minimum point of the AC curve.' },
      { q: 'Define allocative efficiency.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) Resources are allocated to produce the goods consumers value most / occurs where P = MC.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the deadweight loss caused by a profit-maximising monopolist.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Downward-sloping demand (AR) and MR curves drawn. (1) MC/AC curves drawn. (1) Monopoly output at MR = MC and price on the demand curve above that output. (1) Deadweight loss triangle shown between competitive and monopoly output, bounded by demand and MC.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a monopolist might charge a higher price than would prevail under perfect competition.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) A monopolist faces the entire market demand curve and can restrict output. (1) It maximises profit where MR = MC, but price is set on the demand curve above MC. (1) High barriers to entry prevent new firms from competing away supernormal profits.' },
      { q: 'State two barriers to entry that might protect a monopoly.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Patents/intellectual property rights giving legal protection. (1) High sunk costs / large capital requirements deterring entry. (Accept: economies of scale, brand loyalty, control of resources, regulation.)' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by price discrimination and state one condition necessary for it.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Price discrimination is charging different prices to different consumers for the same good/service where cost differences do not justify the price difference. (1) The firm must have market power / be able to prevent arbitrage/resale between groups.' },
      { q: 'Explain why firms in an oligopoly tend to engage in non-price competition.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Oligopolists are interdependent — price cuts may be matched, leading to a price war with no gain in market share. (1) The kinked demand curve suggests price rigidity. (1) Non-price competition (advertising, branding, quality, loyalty schemes) can increase market share without triggering retaliation.' },
      { q: 'Define a contestable market.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) A market where barriers to entry and exit are low or absent. (1) The threat of potential entry is sufficient to influence the behaviour of incumbent firms.' },
      { q: 'Explain how contestability can lead to lower prices even if there is only one firm in the market.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) If barriers to entry are low, the threat of hit-and-run entry exists. (1) If the monopolist charges high prices, new firms will enter and undercut. (1) Therefore the incumbent is disciplined to set prices close to average cost / earn only normal profit.' },
      { q: 'State one advantage and one disadvantage of monopoly for consumers.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Advantage: potential for dynamic efficiency — supernormal profits fund R&D leading to better products. (1) Disadvantage: higher prices and restricted output compared to a competitive market (allocative inefficiency).' },
      { q: 'Draw a diagram showing the kinked demand curve and explain what it shows about price rigidity.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Demand curve with a kink at the current price. (1) More elastic above the kink (price rises not matched) and inelastic below (price cuts matched). (1) Discontinuity/gap in the MR curve at the kink output. (1) MC can shift within the MR gap without changing profit-maximising price — hence price rigidity.' },
      { q: 'Explain one way in which the Competition and Markets Authority (CMA) can promote competition.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The CMA can block mergers/acquisitions that would substantially reduce competition. (1) This prevents excessive concentration and protects consumer choice and competitive pricing.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by X-inefficiency.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) When a firm operates above its minimum average cost curve due to organisational slack. (1) This typically occurs under monopoly where lack of competitive pressure reduces the incentive to minimise costs.' },
      { q: 'Distinguish between first-degree and third-degree price discrimination.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) First-degree: charging each consumer their maximum willingness to pay, extracting all consumer surplus. (1) Third-degree: charging different prices to different identifiable groups based on their PED (e.g., student vs adult tickets).' },
      { q: 'State one similarity and one difference between monopolistic competition and perfect competition.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Similarity: both have low barriers to entry and many firms / both earn only normal profit in the long run. (1) Difference: monopolistic competition has differentiated products, while perfect competition has homogeneous products.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by a Nash equilibrium in the context of game theory.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) A Nash equilibrium is where each player is choosing the best strategy given the strategy of the other player(s). (1) No player has an incentive to unilaterally change their strategy.' },
      { q: 'Draw a diagram showing long-run equilibrium for a firm in monopolistic competition.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Downward-sloping demand (AR) curve and MR curve below it. (1) U-shaped AC and MC curves. (1) Profit-maximising output where MC = MR. (1) AR = AC at the profit-maximising output (tangency condition) showing only normal profit.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a firm in monopolistic competition is allocatively and productively inefficient in the long run.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) P > MC — price exceeds marginal cost, so allocative efficiency is not achieved. (1) The firm does not produce at the minimum of its AC curve (excess capacity), so productive efficiency is not achieved. (1) Product differentiation means the demand curve is downward sloping, creating a gap between AR and MC at profit-maximising output.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by a natural monopoly and why it may be inefficient to break it up.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) A natural monopoly exists where the minimum efficient scale is so large relative to market demand that one firm can supply the entire market at lower average cost than two or more firms. (1) The industry has very high fixed costs and low marginal costs (e.g., water pipes, rail tracks). (1) Breaking it up would lead to wasteful duplication of infrastructure and higher average costs for consumers.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show how third-degree price discrimination works between two market segments.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Two separate demand curves for the two segments (e.g., peak/off-peak or adult/student). (1) One segment has more elastic demand, the other more inelastic. (1) Higher price charged in the inelastic segment, lower price in the elastic segment. (1) Profit maximised in each segment where MR = MC for that segment.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by collusion and state one factor that makes collusion more likely.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Collusion occurs when firms in an oligopoly agree (formally or informally) to restrict competition, typically by fixing prices or limiting output. (1) Collusion is more likely when there are few firms, products are homogeneous, demand is stable, or barriers to entry are high (any one factor).' },
      { q: 'State two characteristics of an oligopoly market structure.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) A few large firms dominate the market / high concentration ratio (e.g., CR5 > 60%). (1) Interdependence — each firm must consider rivals\' reactions when making price/output decisions. (Accept: high barriers to entry, non-price competition, product differentiation.)' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by limit pricing.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Limit pricing is where an incumbent firm sets price low enough to deter new entrants. (1) The price is set just below the level at which a new entrant could cover their costs / make normal profit, so entry would be unprofitable.' },
      { q: 'Explain one argument for and one against the privatisation of a natural monopoly.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) For: private firms have a profit motive to reduce costs, increase efficiency, and innovate. (1) Private ownership introduces market discipline and reduces X-inefficiency. (1) Against: a private natural monopoly may exploit consumers with high prices since competition is not viable. (1) Regulation is needed but regulators face information asymmetry and the risk of regulatory capture.' },
      { q: 'Explain how a prisoners\' dilemma illustrates the tension between collusion and competition in oligopoly.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) In a prisoners\' dilemma, each firm has a dominant strategy to cheat/lower price regardless of what the rival does. (1) If both cooperate (collude), they both earn high profits. (1) If both defect (compete), they both earn lower profits. (1) The Nash equilibrium is for both to defect, even though mutual cooperation would be better — showing why cartels tend to break down.' },
      { q: 'Define dynamic efficiency.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Dynamic efficiency occurs when firms innovate and develop new products/processes over time. (1) It involves using supernormal profits to fund research and development, leading to improved productive efficiency and consumer choice in the future.' },
      { q: 'Explain why perfect competition achieves both allocative and productive efficiency in long-run equilibrium.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) In long-run equilibrium, P = MC (allocative efficiency) because firms produce where MR = MC and MR = AR = P for price takers. (1) P = minimum AC (productive efficiency) because free entry competes away supernormal profit until AR = AC at the minimum. (1) Any firm not at minimum AC would make losses and exit, ensuring all surviving firms are productively efficient.' },
      { q: 'Explain how the concentration ratio is calculated and what a high value indicates.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The N-firm concentration ratio is the combined market share of the N largest firms in an industry. (1) A high value (e.g., CR5 > 60%) indicates an oligopolistic market structure with high market power concentrated among few firms.' },
      { q: 'Explain one reason why tacit collusion (without formal agreement) can be sustained in an oligopoly.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Price leadership — one dominant firm sets the price and others follow, without explicit communication. (1) Firms recognise that price wars are mutually destructive, so they tacitly agree to keep prices stable and compete through non-price means.' },
      { q: 'Evaluate whether monopoly is always against the consumer interest.', marks: 6, markScheme: '(1) Against: monopoly leads to higher prices and lower output than perfect competition (allocative inefficiency / deadweight loss). (1) Against: lack of competitive pressure may lead to X-inefficiency and poor service. (1) For: supernormal profits may fund innovation and R&D (dynamic efficiency) leading to better products. (1) For: economies of scale in natural monopolies mean lower costs than fragmented markets. (1) For: cross-subsidisation — profits from one market can fund loss-making but socially valuable services. (1) Evaluation: the net effect depends on the extent of barriers to entry, the degree of regulation, and whether the firm reinvests profits in innovation.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by hit-and-run entry in a contestable market.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Hit-and-run entry occurs when a firm enters a market to exploit temporarily high profits. (1) When the incumbent responds by lowering prices, the entrant exits without incurring significant losses because sunk costs are low / exit is costless.' },
      { q: 'Draw a diagram showing long-run losses for a firm in perfect competition and explain the adjustment process.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Horizontal AR/MR curve below the AC curve showing losses. (1) Profit-maximising output where MC = MR. (1) Loss shown as the shaded area between AC and AR at that output. (1) Explanation: firms exit in the long run, reducing market supply, raising price until P = AC and normal profit is restored.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by monopoly power and how it differs from a pure monopoly.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Monopoly power refers to the ability of a firm to set prices above marginal cost and earn supernormal profits. (1) A pure monopoly is a single seller with 100% market share. (1) Many firms (oligopolists, dominant firms) can have monopoly power without being a pure monopoly if they face a downward-sloping demand curve / have significant market share.' },
      { q: 'Explain how consumer welfare changes under third-degree price discrimination compared to a single monopoly price.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Some consumers in the elastic segment pay less under price discrimination than they would under a single price — gaining welfare. (1) Some consumers in the inelastic segment pay more — losing welfare. (1) Overall output may increase because the firm sells to consumers who were priced out under the single price. (1) The net welfare effect is ambiguous — it depends on whether the increase in output outweighs the redistribution from consumers to the producer.' }
    ]
  },
  '2.1': {
    name: 'National & International Economy',
    questions: [
      { q: 'Define GDP.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) The total value of all goods and services produced within a country in a given time period (usually a year).' },
      { q: 'Distinguish between nominal and real GDP.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Nominal GDP is measured at current prices / not adjusted for inflation. (1) Real GDP is adjusted for inflation / measured at constant prices, allowing meaningful comparison over time.' },
      { q: 'State two causes of cost-push inflation.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Rising raw material/energy costs (e.g., oil price increase). (1) Wage increases above productivity growth. (Accept: depreciation raising import costs, higher indirect taxes.)' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between cyclical and structural unemployment.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Cyclical unemployment is caused by a fall in aggregate demand during a recession — it is temporary and follows the economic cycle. (1) Structural unemployment is caused by long-term changes in the economy (e.g., decline of industries, skills mismatch). (1) Structural unemployment persists even during economic growth / requires different policy solutions.' },
      { q: 'State the components of the current account of the balance of payments.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Trade in goods and trade in services. (1) Primary income (investment income) and secondary income (transfers).' },
      { q: 'Explain one cost and one benefit of inflation at 2%.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Cost: even moderate inflation erodes the purchasing power of those on fixed incomes or savings. (1) Benefit: moderate inflation allows real wages to adjust downwards without nominal cuts, facilitating labour market flexibility.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by the natural rate of unemployment.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The level of unemployment that persists when the labour market is in equilibrium / at full employment. (1) It consists of frictional and structural unemployment — the rate consistent with stable inflation.' },
      { q: 'State one limitation of the claimant count as a measure of unemployment.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) It undercounts unemployment because not all jobless people are eligible for or claim benefits (e.g., those with working partners, or discouraged workers).' },
      { q: 'Explain how a current account deficit can be caused by an overvalued exchange rate.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) An overvalued exchange rate makes exports more expensive in foreign currency. (1) This reduces the competitiveness of exports, reducing export volume. (1) Imports become cheaper, increasing import volume — worsening the trade balance.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between a positive and a negative output gap.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) A positive output gap occurs when actual GDP exceeds potential GDP — the economy is overheating with inflationary pressure. (1) A negative output gap occurs when actual GDP is below potential — there is spare capacity and likely higher unemployment.' },
      { q: 'Draw a diagram of the economic/business cycle and label the four phases.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Wave-like diagram showing GDP over time with a trend line. (1) Four phases correctly labelled: boom/peak, recession/contraction, slump/trough, recovery/expansion. (1) Actual GDP shown fluctuating above and below trend.' },
      { q: 'Explain one reason why CPI may not accurately reflect the true rate of inflation.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The CPI basket is based on average household spending, which may not reflect individual households\' spending patterns. (1) Substitution bias — consumers switch to cheaper alternatives when prices rise, but the basket may not immediately reflect this.' },
      { q: 'State two consequences of deflation for an economy.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Consumers may delay purchases expecting further price falls, reducing aggregate demand. (1) The real value of debt increases, burdening borrowers and potentially leading to defaults.' },
      { q: 'Explain the accelerator effect.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The accelerator theory states that investment is a function of changes in the rate of GDP growth (not the level). (1) When GDP growth accelerates, investment increases more than proportionally to meet expected future demand. (1) When growth slows, investment can fall sharply even if GDP is still rising.' },
      { q: 'Explain one demand-side and one supply-side cause of a current account deficit.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Demand-side: excessive consumer spending on imports driven by credit availability or rising incomes. (1) Supply-side: poor productivity or lack of competitiveness meaning domestic goods are less attractive than imports.' },
      { q: 'State what the Phillips curve shows.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) The Phillips curve shows an inverse/trade-off relationship between the rate of unemployment and the rate of inflation (or wage inflation) in the short run.' },
      { q: 'Explain why hysteresis can make unemployment more difficult to reduce.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Hysteresis means prolonged unemployment causes permanent damage to workers\' skills and employability. (1) Long-term unemployed may become discouraged and stop searching for work. (1) This increases the natural rate of unemployment, making it harder to reduce even when demand recovers.' },
      { q: 'Calculate GDP using the expenditure method given: C = £1,200bn, I = £350bn, G = £400bn, X = £500bn, M = £550bn.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) GDP = C + I + G + (X - M) = 1200 + 350 + 400 + (500 - 550). (1) GDP = £1,900bn.' },
      { q: 'Explain why GDP per capita may be a better measure of living standards than total GDP.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) GDP per capita divides total output by population, giving an average per person. (1) A country could have high total GDP but low living standards if the population is very large.' },
      { q: 'State two components of the HDI.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Life expectancy at birth (health). (1) Mean years of schooling / expected years of schooling (education). (Accept: GNI per capita at PPP for income.)' },
      { q: 'Define frictional unemployment.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) Short-term unemployment that arises when workers are between jobs / searching for a new job that matches their skills and preferences.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between demand-pull and cost-push inflation.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Demand-pull inflation is caused by excess aggregate demand growing faster than aggregate supply. (1) Cost-push inflation is caused by increases in the costs of production (e.g., wages, raw materials) that shift SRAS left. (1) Demand-pull is associated with economic growth; cost-push can cause stagflation (rising prices with falling output).' },
      { q: 'State the three methods of measuring GDP and explain why they should give the same result.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Income method, output method, and expenditure method. (1) They should give the same result because every pound spent (expenditure) is earned by someone (income) and represents production (output). (1) This is the circular flow of income identity.' },
      { q: 'Explain one reason why a persistent current account deficit might be a problem for an economy.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) A persistent deficit must be financed by capital inflows (borrowing or selling assets to foreigners). (1) This increases external debt / foreign ownership of domestic assets, which may be unsustainable and could lead to a sudden loss of confidence / currency crisis.' },
      { q: 'Draw a diagram showing the Phillips curve and explain the trade-off it represents.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Downward-sloping curve with inflation on the vertical axis and unemployment on the horizontal axis. (1) Shows an inverse relationship — lower unemployment is associated with higher inflation. (1) Policy makers may face a choice between accepting higher inflation to reduce unemployment, or vice versa.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by involuntary unemployment.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Involuntary unemployment occurs when workers are willing and able to work at the prevailing wage rate but cannot find employment. (1) This exists when demand for labour is insufficient / real wages are above the market-clearing level (e.g., due to minimum wage or trade union power).' },
      { q: 'Explain why GDP may overstate economic welfare.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) GDP does not account for negative externalities (e.g., pollution, environmental degradation) that reduce welfare. (1) It does not measure the distribution of income — high GDP may coexist with extreme inequality. (1) It includes defensive expenditure (e.g., spending on crime prevention, cleaning up disasters) that does not improve welfare.' },
      { q: 'State two causes of demand-pull inflation.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) A cut in interest rates encouraging borrowing and spending. (1) Expansionary fiscal policy (tax cuts or increased government spending). (Accept: rising consumer confidence, asset price booms, export growth, excessive money supply growth.)' },
      { q: 'Explain how seasonal unemployment differs from frictional unemployment.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Seasonal unemployment occurs at predictable times of year when demand for certain workers falls (e.g., tourism workers in winter, agricultural workers after harvest). (1) Frictional unemployment is not seasonal — it occurs at any time as workers voluntarily move between jobs / search for better matches.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by underemployment and why it is a limitation of unemployment statistics.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Underemployment occurs when workers have jobs but are working fewer hours than they want or in roles below their skill level. (1) Unemployment statistics count these people as employed, overstating the true health of the labour market / understating spare capacity.' },
      { q: 'Explain the significance of the balance of payments always balancing overall.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The current account and the capital/financial account are mirror images — a deficit on one must be matched by a surplus on the other. (1) If a country imports more than it exports (current account deficit), it must attract capital inflows or run down reserves (financial account surplus). (1) This means a current account deficit is sustainable only as long as foreigners are willing to invest in / lend to that country.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the long-run Phillips curve is considered to be vertical by monetarists.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Monetarists argue there is no long-run trade-off between inflation and unemployment. (1) In the long run, workers adjust their inflation expectations — any attempt to reduce unemployment below the natural rate leads only to accelerating inflation. (1) The LRPC is vertical at the natural rate (NAIRU), meaning unemployment returns to this level regardless of inflation.' },
      { q: 'State the difference between GNI and GDP.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) GDP measures the value of output produced within a country\'s borders regardless of who owns the factors. (1) GNI (Gross National Income) measures income earned by a country\'s residents/nationals regardless of where in the world they earn it — GDP plus net income from abroad.' },
      { q: 'Explain how an ageing population might affect the dependency ratio and economic growth.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) An ageing population increases the dependency ratio (more economically inactive dependents per worker). (1) This increases government spending on pensions and healthcare while the tax base shrinks. (1) Labour force growth slows, potentially reducing the economy\'s productive potential and long-run growth rate.' },
      { q: 'Explain one reason why a current account surplus might be considered a problem.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) A large surplus may indicate insufficient domestic demand / underinvestment / excessive saving domestically. (1) It can lead to trade tensions with other countries who view it as unfair competitive advantage (e.g., through currency manipulation or suppressed wages).' },
      { q: 'Explain how the multiplier-accelerator interaction can cause business cycles.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) An initial increase in autonomous spending is multiplied through the circular flow, increasing national income. (1) Rising income triggers the accelerator — investment rises more than proportionally. (1) Higher investment further multiplies income, creating a cumulative boom. (1) When growth slows, the accelerator causes investment to fall sharply, the multiplier amplifies the decline, and a recession follows — creating cyclical fluctuations.' },
      { q: 'State two limitations of GDP as a measure of living standards.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) GDP does not measure non-market activity (e.g., unpaid care, voluntary work, subsistence farming). (1) GDP does not account for income inequality — a high average may mask widespread poverty. (Accept: does not measure leisure time, quality of life, sustainability, or environmental degradation.)' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by the output gap and why it matters for policy.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The output gap is the difference between actual GDP and potential/trend GDP. (1) A negative output gap (spare capacity) suggests scope for expansionary policy without causing inflation. (1) A positive output gap (overheating) suggests contractionary policy is needed to control inflation — it guides the timing and direction of macroeconomic policy.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between the ILO measure and the claimant count measure of unemployment.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The ILO/Labour Force Survey counts anyone without a job who has actively sought work in the last 4 weeks and is available to start within 2 weeks. (1) The claimant count counts only those claiming unemployment-related benefits. (1) The ILO measure is broader and internationally comparable, while the claimant count is affected by eligibility rules and benefit policy changes.' },
      { q: 'Explain one reason why economic growth does not necessarily lead to economic development.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Growth may be concentrated in extractive industries with profits accruing to foreign firms or elites rather than the population. (1) Without redistribution, investment in public services, or structural change, growth can increase inequality and fail to improve health, education, or poverty reduction.' }
    ]
  },
  '2.2': {
    name: 'AD/AS & Equilibrium',
    questions: [
      { q: 'State the formula for aggregate demand.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) AD = C + I + G + (X - M).' },
      { q: 'Explain one reason why the AD curve slopes downward.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The wealth/real balance effect: as the price level rises, the real value of savings/wealth falls. (1) This reduces consumer spending/consumption, leading to lower aggregate demand.' },
      { q: 'State two factors that could cause the AD curve to shift to the right.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) A cut in interest rates — encouraging borrowing, consumption, and investment. (1) An increase in government spending. (Accept: rise in consumer confidence, tax cuts, depreciation of the exchange rate, rise in overseas incomes.)' },
      { q: 'Explain why the short-run aggregate supply curve is upward sloping.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) In the short run, some costs (e.g., wages) are sticky/fixed by contract. (1) As the price level rises, firms can sell output at higher prices while costs remain unchanged, increasing profit and incentivising greater output.' },
      { q: 'State why the classical LRAS curve is vertical.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) In the long run, the economy\'s output is determined by the quality and quantity of factors of production, not the price level. (1) Changes in the price level lead to proportional changes in wages and costs, so real output is unaffected.' },
      { q: 'Using an AD/AS diagram, show the effect of an increase in government spending on the economy when there is significant spare capacity.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Initial equilibrium in the horizontal/Keynesian region of the AS curve. (1) AD shifts to the right (AD to AD1). (1) Real output increases significantly. (1) The price level remains roughly unchanged / increases only slightly.' },
      { q: 'Using an AD/AS diagram, show the effect of an increase in government spending when the economy is near full capacity.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Initial equilibrium near the vertical section of AS / close to LRAS. (1) AD shifts to the right. (1) The price level rises significantly (demand-pull inflation). (1) Real output increases only marginally / not at all in the classical model.' },
      { q: 'Define the multiplier.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The ratio of the final change in national income to the initial change in spending/injection. (1) Formula: k = 1/(1-MPC) or 1/MPW.' },
      { q: 'If the MPC = 0.75, calculate the value of the multiplier.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) k = 1 / (1 - MPC) = 1 / (1 - 0.75) = 1 / 0.25. (1) k = 4.' },
      { q: 'Government spending increases by £10bn and the multiplier is 2.5. Calculate the final increase in national income.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) Final increase = £10bn x 2.5 = £25bn.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the multiplier is likely to be smaller in a more open economy.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) In an open economy, a greater proportion of additional income leaks out through spending on imports (higher MPM). (1) This reduces the amount re-spent domestically in each round, reducing the size of the multiplier.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by crowding out.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) When increased government spending/borrowing leads to higher interest rates. (1) This reduces private sector investment and consumption, partially or fully offsetting the expansionary effect of the government spending.' },
      { q: 'Draw an AD/AS diagram showing the effect of a supply-side improvement (e.g., better education) on the economy.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Initial equilibrium with AD, SRAS, and LRAS. (1) LRAS shifts to the right (and possibly SRAS). (1) New equilibrium shows higher real output and potentially a lower price level.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between a deflationary gap and an inflationary gap.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) A deflationary gap occurs when AD is below the full employment level — actual output is below potential, with spare capacity and higher unemployment. (1) An inflationary gap occurs when AD exceeds the full employment level — the economy is overheating with upward pressure on prices.' },
      { q: 'State two injections into the circular flow of income.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Investment (I) — spending by firms on capital goods. (1) Government spending (G) / Exports (X). (Any two of I, G, X.)' },
      { q: 'Explain how a rise in consumer confidence would be shown on an AD/AS diagram and its likely effects.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Higher consumer confidence increases consumption (C), a component of AD. (1) AD shifts to the right. (1) This leads to higher real output and/or a higher price level depending on how close the economy is to full capacity.' },
      { q: 'Explain the paradox of thrift.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) If individual households decide to save more (rational for each individual). (1) Total consumption falls, reducing aggregate demand. (1) This leads to lower national income and potentially higher unemployment — a worse outcome for the economy as a whole.' },
      { q: 'State two factors that would shift the LRAS curve to the right.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Improvements in technology/innovation increasing productivity. (1) Investment in education and training improving human capital. (Accept: discovery of new resources, net immigration of skilled workers, institutional improvements.)' },
      { q: 'Explain why Keynesian economists believe the economy can remain in equilibrium below full employment.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Wages and prices are sticky downwards — they do not adjust quickly to clear markets. (1) If AD is insufficient, firms reduce output and employment rather than cutting wages. (1) Without active policy intervention, the economy can persist in a state of deficient demand with involuntary unemployment.' },
      { q: 'State the formula for the marginal propensity to withdraw.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) MPW = MPS + MPT + MPM (marginal propensity to save + marginal propensity to tax + marginal propensity to import).' },
      { q: 'Draw a Keynesian 45-degree line diagram showing equilibrium national income.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) 45-degree line drawn from the origin (where planned expenditure = national income). (1) Aggregate expenditure (C + I + G + X - M) line drawn with positive intercept and slope less than 45 degrees. (1) Equilibrium at the intersection of the AE line and the 45-degree line. (1) Equilibrium national income correctly identified on the horizontal axis.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between the Keynesian and classical views of the LRAS curve.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Classical view: LRAS is vertical at the full employment level of output — the economy always returns to full employment in the long run through flexible wages and prices. (1) Keynesian view: LRAS has a horizontal section (spare capacity), an upward-sloping section (approaching full employment), and a vertical section (full capacity). (1) Keynesians argue the economy can get stuck in the horizontal section with persistent unemployment.' },
      { q: 'Using an AD/AS diagram, show the effect of a global oil price shock on the UK economy.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Initial equilibrium with AD and SRAS. (1) SRAS shifts to the left (higher costs of production). (1) New equilibrium shows a higher price level (cost-push inflation). (1) New equilibrium shows lower real output (fall in GDP) — demonstrating stagflation.' },
      { q: 'Explain what determines the size of the multiplier in practice.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The marginal propensity to consume — a higher MPC means more spending in each round, increasing the multiplier. (1) The tax rate — higher taxes withdraw more income from the circular flow in each round, reducing the multiplier. (1) The marginal propensity to import — more spending on imports leaks demand abroad, reducing the domestic multiplier.' },
      { q: 'Explain the wealth effect as a reason for the downward-sloping AD curve.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) When the price level falls, the real value of household wealth (savings, bonds) increases. (1) Consumers feel wealthier and increase spending, raising the quantity of real output demanded.' },
      { q: 'Explain the international trade effect as a reason for the downward-sloping AD curve.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) When the domestic price level rises relative to other countries, domestic goods become less competitive. (1) Exports fall and imports rise, reducing the net exports component of AD and lowering the quantity of real output demanded.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a negative multiplier effect might follow a decrease in government spending.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) A cut in government spending directly reduces AD. (1) Those who lose income (e.g., public sector workers, government contractors) reduce their own spending. (1) This creates further rounds of reduced spending, leading to a final fall in national income greater than the initial cut — the negative multiplier effect.' },
      { q: 'Using an AD/AS diagram, show how a simultaneous shift right of both AD and LRAS leads to non-inflationary growth.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Initial equilibrium shown. (1) Both AD and LRAS shift to the right by similar amounts. (1) New equilibrium shows higher real output with the price level remaining approximately stable.' },
      { q: 'State the three withdrawals (leakages) from the circular flow of income.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Savings (S) — income not spent on consumption by households. (1) Taxation (T) — income taken by the government. (1) Imports (M) — spending that goes to foreign producers rather than domestic ones.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the actual multiplier in an economy is likely to be smaller than the theoretical value calculated from MPC alone.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The theoretical multiplier (1/(1-MPC)) ignores other leakages — taxation and imports reduce the amount re-spent domestically. (1) Spare capacity may not exist, so increased spending leads to inflation rather than output growth. (1) Time lags and uncertainty mean some additional income may be saved rather than spent, especially during recessions when confidence is low.' },
      { q: 'Explain how an increase in the savings ratio might affect the economy in both the short run and long run.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Short run: higher savings reduce consumption, decreasing AD and potentially causing a recession/rising unemployment (paradox of thrift). (1) Short run: the multiplier works in reverse — each pound saved reduces circular flow income by more than £1. (1) Long run: higher savings provide funds for investment (via the banking system), increasing the capital stock. (1) Long run: greater investment shifts LRAS right, increasing potential output and long-run growth.' },
      { q: 'Draw a circular flow of income diagram showing injections and withdrawals.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Inner flow showing income flowing from firms to households and spending flowing from households to firms. (1) Withdrawals shown leaving the flow: savings (S), taxation (T), imports (M). (1) Injections shown entering the flow: investment (I), government spending (G), exports (X). (1) Equilibrium condition noted: total injections = total withdrawals (I + G + X = S + T + M).' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between autonomous and induced consumption.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Autonomous consumption is spending that occurs regardless of income level (e.g., essential spending financed by borrowing or savings). (1) Induced consumption is spending that rises as income rises — it is determined by the marginal propensity to consume and the level of income.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the SRAS curve might shift to the left.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) An increase in costs of production that affect the whole economy (e.g., higher oil prices, wage increases, depreciation of the exchange rate). (1) This means firms require a higher price level to produce the same quantity of output / at each price level, firms are willing to produce less.' },
      { q: 'Explain how the economy self-corrects from a negative output gap according to the classical/new classical view.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) A negative output gap means actual output is below potential with unemployment above the natural rate. (1) With excess labour supply, wages begin to fall (flexible wages assumption). (1) Lower wages reduce firms\' costs of production, shifting SRAS to the right. (1) SRAS shifts until the economy returns to full employment on the LRAS, with a lower price level.' },
      { q: 'Using an AD/AS diagram, show the impact of a large increase in consumer debt on the economy.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Initially, rising consumer debt increases consumption and shifts AD to the right, raising output and prices. (1) When consumers begin to deleverage (repay debt and reduce spending), AD shifts sharply to the left. (1) This causes a fall in real output (recession) and potentially deflation. (1) Diagram shows the economy moving from an overheated position to a negative output gap.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the multiplier effect takes time to work through the economy.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Each round of the multiplier requires income to be received, decisions to be made, and spending to occur — this takes time. (1) Firms may not immediately hire more workers or expand production in response to increased demand, and consumers may save rather than spend additional income initially.' },
      { q: 'Explain one reason why a shift in AD might have a different effect on the economy depending on where the initial equilibrium is.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) If the economy starts with significant spare capacity (Keynesian horizontal AS section), a rightward shift in AD mainly increases output with little inflation. (1) If the economy starts near full capacity (classical vertical section), a rightward shift mainly causes inflation with little output gain. (1) This demonstrates why the same policy can have different outcomes depending on the state of the economy / the position on the AS curve.' },
      { q: 'Calculate the multiplier if the MPS is 0.1, the tax rate is 0.2, and the MPM is 0.2.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) MPW = MPS + MPT + MPM = 0.1 + 0.2 + 0.2 = 0.5. (1) Multiplier = 1/MPW = 1/0.5 = 2.' },
      { q: 'Explain how expectations of future inflation can themselves cause inflation (self-fulfilling prophecy).', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) If workers expect prices to rise, they demand higher wages to maintain real income. (1) Higher wages increase firms\' costs, causing them to raise prices (cost-push inflation). (1) This confirms the original expectation, leading to further wage demands — creating a wage-price spiral / inflation becomes embedded in expectations.' }
    ]
  },
  '2.3': {
    name: 'Economic Policy',
    questions: [
      { q: 'Define fiscal policy.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) The use of government spending and taxation to influence the level of aggregate demand / economic activity.' },
      { q: 'State one expansionary and one contractionary fiscal policy measure.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Expansionary: cutting income tax / increasing government spending. (1) Contractionary: raising taxes / cutting government spending.' },
      { q: 'Define monetary policy.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) The use of interest rates and the money supply by the central bank to influence aggregate demand, inflation, and economic activity.' },
      { q: 'Explain one way in which a cut in interest rates stimulates aggregate demand.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Lower interest rates reduce the cost of borrowing for firms and households. (1) This encourages investment by firms and consumer spending (especially on credit-sensitive items like cars and housing), increasing AD.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by the transmission mechanism of monetary policy.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The channels through which a change in the base interest rate affects the real economy. (1) Includes effects on: saving/borrowing costs, exchange rates, asset prices, and confidence. (1) These changes influence consumption, investment, net exports, and ultimately aggregate demand, output, and inflation.' },
      { q: 'State two examples of supply-side policies.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Investment in education and training to improve labour productivity. (1) Deregulation to increase competition and reduce barriers to entry. (Accept: privatisation, tax reform, infrastructure spending, trade union reform, welfare reform.)' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between market-based and interventionist supply-side policies.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Market-based policies work by increasing the role of market forces: deregulation, privatisation, reducing taxes, flexible labour markets. (1) Interventionist policies involve active government spending/action: infrastructure investment, education funding, industrial strategy. (1) Market-based aim to free up markets; interventionist aim to correct market failures in factor markets.' },
      { q: 'Explain how automatic stabilisers help to moderate the economic cycle.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) In a recession, tax receipts fall automatically (less income = less tax) and benefit payments rise (more unemployed). (1) This injects spending into the economy without deliberate policy changes, supporting AD. (1) In a boom, the reverse occurs — higher tax and lower benefits dampen demand, reducing inflationary pressure.' },
      { q: 'Explain one limitation of using fiscal policy to manage aggregate demand.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Time lags — it takes time to identify the problem, design policy, pass legislation, and for spending to have an effect. (1) By the time fiscal policy takes effect, economic conditions may have changed, making the policy inappropriate / pro-cyclical.' },
      { q: 'State what the Laffer curve shows.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The Laffer curve shows the relationship between tax rates and total tax revenue. (1) It suggests that beyond a certain tax rate, higher rates reduce revenue because they discourage work, investment, or encourage tax avoidance.' },
      { q: 'Draw a diagram of the Laffer curve and label the revenue-maximising tax rate.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Axes: tax rate (%) on horizontal, tax revenue on vertical. (1) Inverted U-shape / bell curve drawn. (1) Revenue-maximising point labelled at the peak.' },
      { q: 'Explain how quantitative easing is intended to stimulate the economy.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The central bank creates new money to purchase government bonds / financial assets. (1) This increases the money supply and reduces long-term interest rates. (1) Banks have more liquidity to lend, and lower yields encourage borrowing, investment, and spending.' },
      { q: 'Explain one conflict between the objectives of low inflation and low unemployment.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The Phillips curve suggests a short-run trade-off: reducing unemployment requires expansionary policy that increases AD. (1) Higher AD near full capacity causes demand-pull inflation. (1) Conversely, reducing inflation requires contractionary policy that may increase unemployment.' },
      { q: 'Explain why some economists argue for an independent central bank.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Independence removes political pressure to cut rates before elections (political business cycle). (1) It enhances credibility of inflation targeting, anchoring expectations. (1) Lower inflation expectations can reduce the cost of keeping inflation low.' },
      { q: 'State one advantage and one disadvantage of progressive taxation.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Advantage: it reduces income inequality by taking a greater proportion from higher earners. (1) Disadvantage: it may reduce incentives to work, earn, or invest at higher income levels if marginal rates are very high.' },
      { q: 'Explain one way in which supply-side policies can address unemployment.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Education and retraining can reduce structural unemployment by equipping workers with skills demanded by growing industries. (1) This reduces the mismatch between workers\' skills and job requirements, lowering the natural rate of unemployment.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by crowding out and when it is most likely to occur.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Crowding out occurs when government borrowing increases interest rates, reducing private investment and consumption. (1) It is most likely when the economy is close to full capacity. (1) It is less likely when there is significant spare capacity and interest rates are low / at the zero lower bound.' },
      { q: 'State one advantage of using rules-based fiscal policy over discretionary fiscal policy.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) Rules-based policy provides certainty and credibility to markets, reducing risk premiums on government bonds / preventing political manipulation of spending for electoral gain.' },
      { q: 'Explain how a depreciation of the exchange rate could conflict with the inflation target.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) A depreciation makes imports more expensive, directly raising CPI. (1) Higher imported input costs push up domestic production costs (cost-push inflation). (1) This may push inflation above target, requiring the central bank to raise rates, which could slow growth.' },
      { q: 'State what is meant by the government budget deficit and distinguish it from the national debt.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The budget deficit is the excess of government spending over tax revenue in a single year (a flow). (1) The national debt is the total accumulated stock of past budget deficits — the total amount the government owes.' },
      { q: 'Explain the liquidity trap and why it limits the effectiveness of monetary policy.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) A liquidity trap occurs when interest rates are at or near zero (zero lower bound) and cannot be cut further. (1) Consumers and firms prefer to hold cash rather than invest/spend because returns are negligible and confidence is low. (1) Conventional monetary policy becomes ineffective — increasing the money supply does not stimulate lending or spending.' },
      { q: 'Explain one argument in favour of austerity during a period of high government debt.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Reducing the deficit lowers government borrowing, which can reduce interest rates and restore market confidence in public finances. (1) Lower debt-to-GDP reduces interest payments, freeing fiscal space for future spending and reducing the burden on future generations.' },
      { q: 'Explain one argument against austerity during a recession.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Cutting spending during a recession further reduces aggregate demand, deepening the downturn and increasing unemployment (negative multiplier effect). (1) Lower output reduces tax revenue, potentially worsening the deficit ratio — self-defeating fiscal consolidation.' },
      { q: 'Explain how forward guidance works as a monetary policy tool.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Forward guidance involves the central bank communicating its intentions for future interest rate policy. (1) By committing to keep rates low for an extended period, it reduces uncertainty and encourages firms to invest and consumers to spend. (1) It works through expectations — if agents believe rates will stay low, they make spending decisions based on this, stimulating AD today.' },
      { q: 'Evaluate the effectiveness of supply-side policies in reducing unemployment.', marks: 6, markScheme: '(1) Education and training reduce structural unemployment by addressing skills mismatches. (1) Deregulation and reducing barriers to entry create new job opportunities. (1) However, supply-side policies have significant time lags — retraining takes years to yield results. (1) They do not address cyclical unemployment caused by deficient demand. (1) Market-based policies (e.g., reducing benefits) may increase inequality and poverty even if they reduce unemployment figures. (1) Evaluation: most effective in the long run and when combined with demand-side policies to address immediate job losses.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by the zero lower bound problem.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The zero lower bound is the point at which nominal interest rates cannot be reduced further (at or near 0%). (1) This limits conventional monetary policy because the central bank cannot cut rates to stimulate borrowing and spending during severe recessions.' },
      { q: 'Explain one potential negative consequence of quantitative easing.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) QE inflates asset prices (shares, property), disproportionately benefiting the wealthy who hold these assets — increasing wealth inequality. (1) If QE feeds into the money supply without a corresponding increase in output, it risks future inflation when confidence returns. (Accept: weakening the currency excessively, creating asset bubbles, moral hazard for banks.)' },
      { q: 'Explain how a change in indirect taxes affects both AD and AS.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) An increase in indirect taxes (e.g., VAT) raises the price level directly, shifting SRAS to the left (higher costs for firms). (1) It also reduces real disposable income and consumer spending, potentially shifting AD to the left. (1) The net effect on output is contractionary, while the price level may rise (due to supply shift) or fall (due to demand shift) depending on magnitudes.' },
      { q: 'Explain the conflict between economic growth and environmental sustainability.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Rapid economic growth typically increases production and consumption, raising carbon emissions, resource depletion, and pollution. (1) Policies to protect the environment (carbon taxes, regulation) may increase costs for firms, reducing output and slowing growth. (1) However, some argue green investment and innovation can create sustainable growth — the conflict is not necessarily permanent.' },
      { q: 'State two fiscal rules a government might follow and explain their purpose.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Balanced budget rule — current spending should not exceed tax revenue (to prevent unsustainable borrowing). (1) Debt-to-GDP target — national debt should not exceed a certain percentage of GDP (e.g., 60%). (1) Purpose: to maintain fiscal credibility, anchor market expectations, and ensure long-term sustainability of public finances.' },
      { q: 'Explain how negative interest rates are intended to work and one problem with them.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Negative interest rates charge banks for holding reserves at the central bank, incentivising them to lend to businesses and consumers instead. (1) This aims to stimulate borrowing and spending when conventional rate cuts have reached the zero bound. (1) Problem: banks may be reluctant to pass negative rates to depositors (who would withdraw cash), squeezing bank profits and potentially reducing lending — the opposite of the intended effect.' },
      { q: 'Explain why supply-side policies might not reduce inflation in the short run.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Supply-side policies (e.g., education, infrastructure) take years to increase productive capacity. (1) In the short run, inflationary pressures from excess demand persist because LRAS has not yet shifted — only demand management can address inflation quickly.' },
      { q: 'Evaluate the use of fiscal policy versus monetary policy to stimulate an economy in recession.', marks: 6, markScheme: '(1) Fiscal policy (spending increases/tax cuts) directly boosts AD and can be targeted at specific sectors or regions. (1) Monetary policy (rate cuts) works through the transmission mechanism and relies on banks lending and consumers/firms borrowing. (1) In a liquidity trap, monetary policy may be ineffective (pushing on a string), giving fiscal policy an advantage. (1) Fiscal policy suffers from longer implementation lags (legislation) compared to monetary policy (MPC meets monthly). (1) Fiscal expansion may increase government debt and risk crowding out (less of a concern at the zero bound). (1) Evaluation: at the zero lower bound in a severe recession, fiscal policy is likely more effective; in normal times, monetary policy is more flexible and less politically constrained.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by the structural budget deficit and why it matters.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The structural deficit is the part of the budget deficit that remains even when the economy is at full employment — it is not caused by the economic cycle. (1) It matters because it indicates the government is spending beyond its means in a sustainable sense, requiring future tax rises or spending cuts regardless of economic conditions.' },
      { q: 'Explain one way in which infrastructure investment acts as both a demand-side and supply-side policy.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Demand-side: government spending on infrastructure directly increases AD (G component) and creates jobs in construction. (1) The multiplier effect amplifies the initial spending through rounds of increased income and consumption. (1) Supply-side: completed infrastructure (roads, railways, broadband) reduces costs for firms, improves productivity, and increases the economy\'s productive potential (shifts LRAS right).' },
      { q: 'Explain why economists disagree about the effectiveness of the Laffer curve.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The shape of the Laffer curve is unknown — no one knows the revenue-maximising tax rate for a given economy. (1) Supply-side economists argue many economies are on the right side (tax rates too high), but evidence is disputed. (1) The revenue-maximising rate depends on many factors (labour market flexibility, tax avoidance opportunities, cultural attitudes) that vary between countries and over time.' },
      { q: 'Explain how macroprudential policy differs from monetary policy.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Macroprudential policy targets the stability of the financial system as a whole (e.g., capital requirements, loan-to-value limits, stress tests). (1) Monetary policy targets inflation and output through interest rates and money supply — macroprudential addresses systemic risk even when monetary policy is appropriately set.' },
      { q: 'Explain one reason why fiscal multipliers might be larger during a recession than during a boom.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) During a recession, there is significant spare capacity — additional spending leads to higher output rather than inflation. (1) At the zero lower bound, crowding out does not occur because interest rates cannot rise in response to government borrowing — so private spending is not displaced.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by the golden rule of fiscal policy.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The government should only borrow to invest (capital spending), not to fund current/day-to-day spending over the economic cycle. (1) This ensures borrowing adds to the economy\'s productive capacity (future growth), while everyday spending is funded from taxation.' },
      { q: 'Explain one risk of relying on monetary policy alone to manage the economy.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Monetary policy operates through interest rates which have blunt, economy-wide effects — it cannot target specific regions, sectors, or groups. (1) Over-reliance on low rates can inflate asset bubbles and increase household debt to unsustainable levels, creating financial instability.' }
    ]
  },
  '2.4': {
    name: 'International Economics & Development',
    questions: [
      { q: 'Define comparative advantage.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The ability of a country to produce a good at a lower opportunity cost (1) than another country.' },
      { q: 'State two assumptions of the theory of comparative advantage.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) There are no transport costs. (1) There are constant returns to scale / only two countries and two goods. (Accept: perfect factor mobility within countries, no trade barriers, full employment.)' },
      { q: 'Explain one benefit of international trade based on comparative advantage.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Countries can specialise in goods where they have lowest opportunity cost. (1) This increases total world output and allows countries to consume beyond their own PPF through trade.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the effect of a tariff on an imported good.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Diagram showing domestic supply and demand with world price below equilibrium. (1) Tariff raises the price from Pw to Pw + tariff. (1) Domestic supply expands and imports contract. (1) Government revenue, deadweight loss, and change in consumer/producer surplus identifiable.' },
      { q: 'Define a floating exchange rate.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) An exchange rate determined solely by market forces of supply and demand for the currency in the foreign exchange market.' },
      { q: 'Explain two factors that could cause the pound sterling to appreciate.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Higher UK interest rates relative to other countries attract hot money inflows / increased demand for sterling. (1) Increased demand for UK exports raises demand for sterling in the forex market. (1) Improved economic performance/higher growth rates attract FDI. (1) Speculation that the pound will rise increases demand for sterling.' },
      { q: 'State one advantage and one disadvantage of a fixed exchange rate.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Advantage: provides certainty for international trade, reducing exchange rate risk and encouraging investment. (1) Disadvantage: requires large foreign currency reserves to defend and limits monetary policy independence.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by protectionism and state one argument in its favour.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Protectionism involves government policies to restrict or discourage imports (tariffs, quotas, subsidies). (1) Infant industry argument: new industries need temporary protection to grow and achieve economies of scale. (1) This allows them to become competitive internationally before protection is removed.' },
      { q: 'Explain how globalisation has affected labour markets in developed countries.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Globalisation has led to outsourcing and offshoring of low-skilled manufacturing jobs to lower-wage countries. (1) This has reduced demand for low-skilled workers in developed economies, contributing to structural unemployment. (1) However, it has created jobs in service sectors and increased demand for high-skilled workers.' },
      { q: 'State two potential costs of globalisation for developing countries.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Increased vulnerability to external economic shocks / contagion from global financial crises. (1) Environmental degradation from resource extraction and industrialisation to serve global markets. (Accept: cultural erosion, exploitation by MNCs, increased inequality, loss of domestic industries.)' },
      { q: 'Distinguish between economic growth and economic development.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Economic growth is an increase in real GDP / national output over time (quantitative). (1) Economic development is a broader concept including improved living standards, reduced poverty, better health/education, and greater equality (qualitative).' },
      { q: 'State two indicators of economic development other than GDP per capita.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) HDI (Human Development Index) incorporating health, education, and income. (1) Literacy rates / infant mortality rates / life expectancy / access to clean water. (Any two valid indicators.)' },
      { q: 'Explain one way in which FDI can promote economic development.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) FDI brings foreign capital which can fund infrastructure, factories, and job creation in developing countries. (1) Technology transfer from MNCs can improve domestic productivity and build local expertise/skills.' },
      { q: 'Explain one way in which FDI might hinder economic development.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Profits may be repatriated to the MNC\'s home country rather than reinvested locally, creating a leakage from the circular flow. (1) MNCs may exploit weak labour/environmental regulations, worsening working conditions or environmental degradation.' },
      { q: 'Define the terms of trade.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The ratio of export prices to import prices. (1) Measured as: (Index of export prices / Index of import prices) x 100.' },
      { q: 'Explain how deteriorating terms of trade can hinder development for a primary commodity exporter.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Deteriorating terms of trade mean export prices fall relative to import prices. (1) The country must export more to buy the same volume of imports. (1) This reduces foreign exchange earnings, limiting the ability to import capital goods, technology, and other inputs needed for development.' },
      { q: 'State what the Gini coefficient measures and what a value of 0.6 indicates.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The Gini coefficient measures income/wealth inequality on a scale from 0 (perfect equality) to 1 (perfect inequality). (1) A value of 0.6 indicates high inequality — a large gap between the richest and poorest.' },
      { q: 'Explain one argument against the use of trade barriers to protect domestic industries.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Trade barriers raise prices for domestic consumers, reducing consumer surplus and living standards. (1) They also protect inefficient firms from competition, reducing incentives to innovate and improve productivity.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by a customs union and how it differs from a free trade area.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) A customs union is a trade bloc where members remove tariffs between themselves and adopt a common external tariff (CET) on imports from non-members. (1) A free trade area removes internal tariffs but each member sets its own external tariffs. (1) The CET means customs union members negotiate trade deals as a single bloc.' },
      { q: 'State two potential benefits of microfinance for economic development.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Provides small loans to entrepreneurs who lack access to formal banking, enabling them to start or expand businesses. (1) Empowers women and marginalised groups, promoting inclusive development and reducing poverty at a local level.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show how a quota restricts imports compared to free trade.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Domestic supply and demand diagram with world price showing level of imports under free trade. (1) Quota limits the quantity of imports to a fixed amount. (1) Effective supply curve becomes domestic supply plus the quota amount — supply becomes vertical at domestic supply + quota. (1) Domestic price rises above world price, reducing consumer surplus and creating a deadweight loss.' },
      { q: 'Explain the J-curve effect following a depreciation of the exchange rate.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Immediately after depreciation, the trade balance initially worsens because import and export volumes are slow to adjust (price inelastic in the short run). (1) The higher cost of imports (in domestic currency) increases the value of imports while export volumes have not yet risen. (1) Over time, exports become more competitive and volumes increase; imports become more expensive and volumes decrease. (1) The trade balance eventually improves, tracing a J-shape over time.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by the Marshall-Lerner condition.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The Marshall-Lerner condition states that a depreciation will improve the trade balance only if the sum of the PED for exports and PED for imports is greater than one. (1) If demand for exports and imports is sufficiently elastic, the volume effect of depreciation outweighs the price effect.' },
      { q: 'Explain two barriers to economic development in sub-Saharan Africa.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Poor institutional quality — corruption, weak rule of law, and insecure property rights deter investment and entrepreneurship. (1) Inadequate infrastructure — lack of roads, reliable electricity, and communications raises costs and limits market access. (1) Commodity dependence — reliance on primary exports exposes economies to volatile world prices and declining terms of trade. (1) Debt burden — high external debt diverts government revenue from health and education to debt servicing.' },
      { q: 'Define absolute advantage and explain how it differs from comparative advantage.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Absolute advantage means a country can produce a good using fewer resources / more efficiently than another country in absolute terms. (1) Comparative advantage is based on opportunity cost — a country can have comparative advantage even without absolute advantage, as long as its opportunity cost of production is lower.' },
      { q: 'Explain how the Harrod-Domar growth model works.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Growth depends on the level of savings in the economy — higher savings provide funds for investment. (1) Investment increases the capital stock, raising productive capacity and output. (1) The rate of growth = savings ratio / capital-output ratio — suggesting developing countries need higher savings or more productive investment to grow faster.' },
      { q: 'Explain one limitation of the Harrod-Domar model.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) It assumes savings are automatically channelled into productive investment — but developing countries may lack functioning banking systems or capital markets. (1) It ignores the role of human capital, technology, governance, and institutional quality in driving growth.' },
      { q: 'Explain how a managed/dirty float exchange rate system works.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The exchange rate is primarily determined by market forces but the central bank intervenes occasionally to influence the rate. (1) Intervention involves buying/selling foreign currency reserves or adjusting interest rates to prevent excessive volatility or misalignment.' },
      { q: 'Explain one way in which corruption hinders economic development.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Corruption diverts public funds away from essential services (health, education, infrastructure) into private hands. (1) It deters foreign investment and aid, as firms face unpredictable costs and donors cannot ensure funds reach intended recipients.' },
      { q: 'Evaluate the role of international aid in promoting economic development.', marks: 6, markScheme: '(1) Aid can fund essential infrastructure, health, and education that governments cannot afford from domestic revenue. (1) Emergency/humanitarian aid saves lives during crises and natural disasters. (1) However, aid dependency can reduce incentives for governments to raise domestic tax revenue or implement reforms. (1) Aid may be tied to donor conditions that do not align with the recipient country\'s priorities. (1) Corruption may divert aid from intended beneficiaries. (1) Evaluation: aid is most effective when targeted, conditional on good governance, and accompanied by institutional reform — it is neither universally helpful nor universally harmful.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by trade creation and trade diversion in the context of a customs union.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Trade creation occurs when the removal of internal tariffs allows members to import from a more efficient member country instead of producing domestically. (1) Trade diversion occurs when the common external tariff causes members to import from a less efficient member rather than a more efficient non-member. (1) A customs union improves welfare if trade creation exceeds trade diversion.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show how an export subsidy affects the domestic and world markets.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Domestic market diagram showing supply and demand with world price. (1) Export subsidy effectively raises the price received by domestic producers above the world price. (1) Domestic production increases and domestic consumption decreases (as price to domestic consumers rises). (1) Increased exports shown, with deadweight loss and government cost of subsidy identifiable.' },
      { q: 'Explain the Prebisch-Singer hypothesis.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The hypothesis states that the terms of trade for primary commodity exporters decline over time relative to manufactured goods exporters. (1) Demand for primary commodities is income inelastic — as world incomes rise, demand grows slowly. (1) Supply of commodities tends to increase (new producers, new technology), keeping prices low — while manufactured goods benefit from innovation and brand differentiation that maintain higher prices.' },
      { q: 'Explain one argument in favour of debt relief for developing countries.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Debt relief frees government revenue from debt servicing, allowing increased spending on health, education, and infrastructure needed for development. (1) It can break the cycle of borrowing to repay old debts, giving countries fiscal space to invest in poverty reduction and growth.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between trade liberalisation and protectionism.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Trade liberalisation involves removing or reducing barriers to international trade (cutting tariffs, eliminating quotas, deregulating). (1) Protectionism involves imposing or increasing barriers to trade to shield domestic industries from foreign competition.' },
      { q: 'Explain how a depreciation of the currency might help reduce a current account deficit.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Depreciation makes exports cheaper in foreign currency, increasing demand for exports. (1) It makes imports more expensive in domestic currency, reducing demand for imports. (1) If the Marshall-Lerner condition holds (PEDx + PEDm > 1), the trade balance improves — though this may take time (J-curve effect).' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by the dependency ratio and how it affects developing countries.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The dependency ratio is the proportion of the population that is economically inactive (children under 16 + elderly) relative to the working-age population. (1) High dependency ratios in developing countries (due to high birth rates) mean fewer workers support more dependents. (1) This limits savings, tax revenue, and investment in productive capacity, constraining economic development.' },
      { q: 'Explain two ways in which education promotes economic development.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Education improves human capital — a more skilled and productive workforce increases output and attracts investment. (1) Educated populations are healthier (better understanding of nutrition, hygiene), reducing healthcare costs and increasing life expectancy. (1) Education empowers women — female education correlates with lower birth rates, higher family incomes, and greater social equality. (1) Education fosters innovation and entrepreneurship, enabling countries to move up the value chain from primary commodities to manufacturing and services.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by the Lewis dual-sector model of development.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Lewis identified two sectors: a traditional agricultural sector with surplus/underemployed labour, and a modern industrial/urban sector. (1) Development occurs as surplus labour moves from agriculture to industry, where productivity and wages are higher. (1) Profits in the industrial sector are reinvested, expanding capacity and absorbing more agricultural labour until the surplus is exhausted.' },
      { q: 'Explain one way in which trade can act as an engine of growth for a developing country.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Access to larger export markets allows firms to exploit economies of scale and specialise in goods where they have comparative advantage. (1) Export revenue provides foreign exchange to import capital goods, technology, and intermediate inputs needed for industrialisation and development.' }
    ]
  }
};
